definition.value: A sialotetraosylceramide consisting of a branched hexasaccharide made up from two sialyl residues, two galactose residues, one N-acetylglucosamine residue and a glucose residue at the reducing end attached to the ceramide portion via a beta-linkage.
A dTDP-sugar having 4-dehydro-2,6-dideoxy-beta-L-glucose as the sugar component.
A dimethylxanthine having the two methyl groups located at positions 1 and 3. It is structurally similar to caffeine and is found in green and black tea.
An aromatic amide that consists of benzene bearing a single carboxamido substituent. The parent of the class of benzamides.
A butynal which has a monosubstituted triple bond.
A 2',3'-cyclic purine nucleotide in which guanosine is used as the parent nucleoside.
A member of the class of imidazoles that is 1H-imidazole substituted by a hydroxymethyl group at position 4.
A flavanone glycoside that consists of fustin attached to a beta-D-galactosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
A member of the class of coumarins that is umbelliferone in which the hydroxy group at position 7 is replaced by an ethoxy group.
A serine derivative in which the alpha-hydrogen of serine is replaced by a hydroxymethyl group.
A hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-methylbut-3-enoic acid.
A glycosylglucose consisting of two D-glucopyranose units connected by an alpha-(1->6)-linkage.
A glucotriose consisting of two alpha-D-glucopyranose residues and a D-glucopyranose residue joined in sequence by (1->4) and (1->6) glycosidic bonds.

The delta-lactam obtained by formal oxidation at the 2-position of sparteine. The major alkaloid from the seeds of Lupinus exaltatus, L. mexicanus and L. rotundiflorus, it is among the most important of the tetracyclic quinolizidine alkaloids.
The cis-isomer of octadec-6-enoic acid, a long-chain fatty acid.
An androstanoid that is 5beta-androstane substituted by an alpha-hydroxy group at position 3 and an oxo group at position 17. It is a metabolite of testosterone in mammals.

An erythromycin that consists of erythronolide B having 2,6-dideoxy-3-C-methyl-3-O-methyl-alpha-L-ribo-hexopyranosyl and 3,4,6-trideoxy-3-(dimethylamino)-beta-D-xylo-hexopyranosyl residues attahced at positions 4 and 6 respectively.
A member of the class of 7-hydroxyisoflavones that is 7-hydroxyisoflavone substituted by an additional hydroxy group at position 4'.
Iron (Fe3+) siderophore
A chloroethanol carrying a chloro substituent at position 2.

A member of the class of rotenones that consists of 1,2,12,12a-tetrahydrochromeno[3,4-b]furo[2,3-h]chromen-6(6aH)-one substituted at position 2 by a prop-1-en-2-yl group and at positions 8 and 9 by methoxy groups (the 2R,6aS,12aS-isomer). A non-systemic insecticide, it is the principal insecticidal constituent of derris (the dried rhizome and root of Derris elliptica).
A hydroxyacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of [hydroxy(phenyl)methyl]succinic acid.
Any hydroxyisoflavone which has a hydroxy group at the 2-position of the phenyl substituent.
A galactosamine phosphate that is D-galactosamine substituted at position 1 by a monophosphate group.
A HETE having a (5S)-hydroxy group and (6E)-, (8Z)-, (11Z)- and (14Z)-double bonds.
A  C20-gibberellin with a heteropentacyclic skeleton that incorporates a lactone moiety.
A chloro-1,3,5-triazine that is  6-chloro-1,3,5-triazine-2,4-diamine in which one of the hydrogens of the amino group is replaced by a propan-2-yl group.
A nitrile that is hydrogen cyanide in which the hydrogen has been replaced by an ethenyl group.
A dihydroxypyridine that is pseudooxynicotine in which the hydrogens at positions 2 and 6 on the pyridine ring are substituted by hydroxy groups.
A trichlorobenzene with chloro substituents at positions 1, 2 and 4.
